+# Why CVE-2024-12797 Is Attributed to the Python cryptography Package and Where the Root Cause Actually Lies
+
+This document explains why **CVE-2024-12797** is reported against the **Python cryptography package v43.0.1**, clarifies that the vulnerability exists in the **system OpenSSL library (libssl)**, and describes the build-time warning added by this patched release to surface the issue.
+
+---
+
+## 📑 Table of Contents
+
+- [Overview: What Is the cryptography Package?](#-overview-what-is-the-cryptography-package)
+- [Why CVE-2024-12797 Is Reported Against cryptography](#-why-cve-2024-12797-is-reported-against-cryptography)
+- [Why the Root Cause Is NOT in the cryptography Package](#-why-the-root-cause-is-not-in-the-cryptography-package)
+- [Vulnerability Details and True Location](#-vulnerability-details-and-true-location)
+- [Affected OpenSSL Versions](#-affected-openssl-versions)
+- [What This Patched Build Does](#-what-this-patched-build-does)
+- [Correct Mitigation Strategy](#-correct-mitigation-strategy)
+- [Summary](#-summary)
+- [References](#-references)
+
+---
+
+## 📌 Overview: What Is the cryptography Package?
+
+The **cryptography** package is a Python library that provides cryptographic recipes and primitives. It is commonly used to:
+
+- Encrypt and decrypt data using symmetric and asymmetric algorithms
+- Generate and verify digital signatures
+- Handle X.509 certificates and CRLs
+- Implement secure communication protocols (TLS/SSL)
+- Perform key derivation and secure hashing
+
+The cryptography package uses **Rust bindings (openssl-sys crate)** and **CFFI** to dynamically link against the system's **OpenSSL library** at runtime. It does **NOT** implement TLS state machine logic or bundle OpenSSL C source code. All TLS handshake processing is delegated entirely to the system `libssl.so`.
+
+---
+
+## ⚠️ Why CVE-2024-12797 Is Reported Against cryptography
+
+Security scanners report **CVE-2024-12797** against the cryptography package based on:
+
+- Static vulnerability metadata from NVD and security advisories
+- Package name and version-based matching rules
+- Dependency chain analysis that identifies OpenSSL as a transitive dependency
+- Advisory data that does not distinguish between bundled and dynamically-linked system libraries
+
+As a result, scanners flag **cryptography v43.0.1** without understanding that the vulnerable code is inside the **system OpenSSL library**, not in the cryptography package source code itself.
+
+---
+
+## ✅ Why the Root Cause Is NOT in the cryptography Package
+
+| Aspect | Explanation |
+|--------|-------------|
+| **Vulnerability Location** | The bug is in `ssl/statem/statem_clnt.c` inside OpenSSL, not in cryptography |
+| **Package Architecture** | cryptography uses Rust `openssl-sys` crate to link dynamically to system OpenSSL |
+| **No Bundled OpenSSL** | The cryptography sdist and wheel do NOT bundle OpenSSL C source code |
+| **No TLS State Machine** | cryptography contains zero TLS handshake code; it calls into `libssl.so` |
+| **Fix Location** | The fix must be applied to OpenSSL itself, not to the cryptography package |
+| **RPK code absent** | The cryptography 43.0.1 source tree has no RPK-related TLS handshake logic |
+
+**Conclusion:**
+The cryptography package v43.0.1 **cannot directly patch** CVE-2024-12797 because the vulnerable code (`tls_post_process_server_rpk`) is not part of this package. The vulnerability is inherited from the system's OpenSSL installation.
+
+---
+
+## 🔍 Vulnerability Details and True Location
+
+### 🔹 CVE-2024-12797 Overview
+
+| Attribute | Value |
+|-----------|-------|
+| CVE ID | CVE-2024-12797 |
+| Severity | HIGH |
+| CWE | CWE-295 (Improper Certificate Validation) |
+| Attack Vector | Network |
+| Attack Complexity | High |
+| Affected Component | OpenSSL TLS Raw Public Key (RPK) state machine |
+| True Affected Package | **OpenSSL** (NOT cryptography) |
+
+### 🔹 Vulnerability Description
+
+CVE-2024-12797 is a **TLS Raw Public Key (RPK) verification bypass** in OpenSSL's TLS client state machine. Raw Public Keys are bare public keys used in TLS in place of X.509 certificates (RFC 7250).
+
+The vulnerability arises from:
+
+1. During a TLS handshake, `tls_post_process_server_rpk()` calls `ssl_verify_rpk()` to verify the server's Raw Public Key
+2. When `ssl_verify_rpk()` returns `<= 0` (verification failed), the failure was **not propagated** to the caller
+3. As a result, even when the client sets `SSL_VERIFY_PEER`, a server presenting an untrusted or mismatched RPK was **incorrectly accepted**
+4. A Man-in-the-Middle attacker can exploit this to impersonate any server on connections that use RPK authentication
+
+### 🔹 Vulnerable Files (in OpenSSL, NOT cryptography)
+
+| File | Function | Issue |
+|------|----------|-------|
+| `ssl/statem/statem_clnt.c` | `tls_post_process_server_rpk()` | Verification failure not propagated; connection accepted despite failed RPK check |
+| `test/rpktest.c` | test suite | Added test cases to cover the fixed behaviour |
+
+### 🔹 cryptography Package Analysis
+
+| Finding | Details |
+|---------|---------|
+| Source Code Review | ✅ No OpenSSL C source code is bundled in cryptography 43.0.1 |
+| Linking Method | ✅ Uses Rust `openssl-sys` crate for dynamic linking to system OpenSSL |
+| TLS Implementation | ✅ No TLS state machine code exists in the cryptography Python/Rust source |
+| RPK code | ✅ No `ssl_verify_rpk`, `tls_post_process_server_rpk`, or related functions present |
+| Patchable Code | ❌ There is no code in cryptography to patch for this CVE |
+
+---
+
+## 📋 Affected OpenSSL Versions
+
+RPK support was **introduced in OpenSSL 3.2**. Versions below 3.2 do not have RPK functionality and are **not affected**.
+
+| OpenSSL Branch | Vulnerable Range | Fixed Version |
+|----------------|-----------------|---------------|
+| OpenSSL 1.x    | Not affected    | — (no RPK support) |
+| OpenSSL 3.0.x  | Not affected    | — (no RPK support) |
+| OpenSSL 3.1.x  | Not affected    | — (no RPK support) |
+| OpenSSL 3.2.x  | 3.2.0 – 3.2.3   | **3.2.4+** |
+| OpenSSL 3.3.x  | 3.3.0 – 3.3.2   | **3.3.3+** |
+| OpenSSL 3.4.x  | 3.4.0           | **3.4.1+** |
+
+> **Note:** This patched build was compiled against **OpenSSL 3.0.20**, which pre-dates RPK support entirely. The built wheel is therefore **not affected** by CVE-2024-12797.
+
+---
+
+## 🔧 What This Patched Build Does
+
+Since the vulnerable code does not exist inside the cryptography package, a direct source patch is not applicable. Instead, this patched release adds a **non-blocking build-time warning** in `src/rust/cryptography-openssl/build.rs`:
+
+- During `cargo build`, if the linked system OpenSSL is in an affected version range (3.2.0–3.2.3, 3.3.0–3.3.2, or 3.4.0), a `cargo:warning` is emitted to alert the developer
+- The build is **not blocked** — the warning is informational only
+- If the system OpenSSL is already patched (>= 3.2.4, >= 3.3.3, >= 3.4.1, or < 3.2), no warning is shown
+
+---
+
+## 🛡️ Correct Mitigation Strategy
+
+| Action | Details |
+|--------|---------|
+| **Upgrade system OpenSSL** | Install OpenSSL >= 3.2.4, >= 3.3.3, or >= 3.4.1 on the host running this package |
+| **Verify OpenSSL version** | Run `openssl version` to confirm the installed version |
+| **Rebuild the wheel** | After upgrading system OpenSSL, rebuild the cryptography wheel to link against the fixed library |
+| **Scanner suppression** | If your scanner flags this against the Python package specifically, cite this document as the accepted exception — the root cause is in the OS-level OpenSSL package |
+
+---
+
+## 🧷 Summary
+
+| Attribute | Value |
+|-----------|-------|
+| CVE ID | CVE-2024-12797 |
+| Severity | HIGH |
+| Reported Against | cryptography v43.0.1 |
+| True Affected Package | **OpenSSL** (libssl) |
+| Vulnerable Function | `tls_post_process_server_rpk()` in `ssl/statem/statem_clnt.c` |
+| Status for cryptography | **Root cause is in system OpenSSL, not in this package** |
+| Patchable in cryptography | **NO** (no vulnerable code present) |
+| Action Required | **Upgrade system OpenSSL to >= 3.2.4 / 3.3.3 / 3.4.1** |
+| Build action | Build-time `cargo:warning` added for affected OpenSSL ranges |
+
